article.headline: Houston 66, Memphis 53
article.story: HOUSTON (AP) -- Brian Latham, Ramon Dyer and Houston played at a pace that even the architect of Phi Slama Jama could appreciate. Latham scored 22 points and Dyer added a career-high 19 points and 11 rebounds, leading the Cougars to a 66-53 victory over Memphis on Saturday. Dyer went 5-of-7 from 3-point range and scored 16 points in the second half, helping Houston (14-9, 5-4 Conference USA) earn its 1,000th win in school history. At the end, Houston coach Tom Penders awarded the game ball to former UH coach Guy V. Lewis, who watched the game from a private booth near the top of Hofheinz Pavilion. The 82-year-old Lewis coached at Houston from 1956-86, compiled a record of 592-279 and went to five Final Fours, including three straight appearances in the early '80s with a team dubbed "Phi Slama Jama" for its fearsome fastbreaks and thunderous dunkers. "It's one of our goals of the program to bring that back," Penders said. "To have over 1,000 wins and to realize that Coach Lewis is probably responsible for 70 percent is unbelievable. Hopefully he will get some credit for this today." Houston improved to 1,000-672 in 60 years of basketball. Anthony Rice and Darius Washington each scored 12 points to lead Memphis (13-10, 6-3), which had its three-game winning streak snapped. Houston won despite shooting 37 percent and getting just eight points from leading scorer Andre Owens, who averages 18.1 points a game. Instead, the Cougars relied on a frenetic, up-and-down the court scheme that seemed to have been lifted from one of Lewis' old playbooks. Memphis, which ranks 13th out of 14 C-USA teams in assist-to-turnover ratio, held a 30-25 halftime lead but was ultimately doomed by tying a season high with 26 turnovers. "They played an aggressive style and we did not respond to it," Memphis coach John Calipari said. "They outhustled us and got all of the loose balls." Penders said, "The officials let us play tonight. That's what the fans want to see ... not a free-throw shooting contest." The Cougars ran off 14 straight points to take a 39-32 lead early in the second half, holding Memphis scoreless for almost seven minutes. During that stretch, the Tigers committed seven turnovers and missed seven shots. Rice hit a 3 to end the Tigers' drought with 11:25 to go, and Memphis quickly tied the score up at 39. But Houston went on another late run, with Dyer hitting a 3 and Latham stealing the ball from Washington and scoring on a layup to give the Cougars a 52-44 lead. Memphis would never get any closer down the stretch. "Coach said to go out and have fun and that's what I was doing today," said Latham, who also had seven rebounds and five steals. "I was just playing my game within the flow of the game."
